    "summary": "The Ayutthaya Kingdom (1350–1767 AD) was the most powerful Thai state of the pre-modern era, founded by King Ramathibodi I in 1350 on the Chao Phraya River delta in central Thailand at a site that became one of the largest and wealthiest cities in Southeast Asia. Absorbing the [[event:2308|Sukhothai Kingdom]] by 1438, Ayutthaya grew to control most of mainland Southeast Asia's western portion, competing with the Khmer, Burmese, and Malay states for regional dominance over four centuries.\n\nAyutthaya's location — at the convergence of rivers, easily defensible by seasonal flooding, and accessible to ocean-going vessels — made it a major hub of Southeast Asian and international trade. Chinese, Japanese, Malay, Persian, Arab, Portuguese (from 1511), Dutch, and English traders all established communities in Ayutthaya, making it one of the most cosmopolitan cities in the 16th–17th century world with a population that may have reached one million. The kingdom developed an elaborate court ceremonial drawing on Khmer Hindu-Buddhist traditions of divine kingship alongside the Theravada Buddhism inherited from Sukhothai, producing a synthesis of religious and political culture that defined Thai monarchical tradition. Ayutthaya was destroyed by the Burmese in 1767 in one of the most complete acts of urban devastation in Southeast Asian history — the temples, palaces, and libraries of a four-century capital were burned and looted, an event of profound cultural trauma for Thailand. The ruins of Ayutthaya (now a UNESCO World Heritage Site) preserve the scale of what was lost.",
